# React components

- Prefer **small, named components** over inline markup when reused or visually complex (e.g. extract SVGs into `*Icon` components).
- Ensure components have their **own file** by default.
  - The exception is when **small compound components** are clearer co-located in the same file.
- Extract non-trivial inline UI widgets (e.g. loaders/indicators) into their own named components.
- **Favour composition over anonymous styled divs.** A `<div className="flex ...">` is imperative — it describes *how* it looks. Replace styled structural wrappers with named layout components that describe *what* they are. Examples:
  - `<AlertLayout>` — a `role="alert"` container with its border, shadow, and flex layout baked in
  - `<AlertBody>` — the content column next to the icon
  - `<AlertMessage>` — the text block for the primary message
  This makes the consuming component read as a description of intent rather than a stylesheet.
  ```tsx
  // Prefer this
  <AlertLayout>
    <WarningIcon />
    <AlertBody>
      <AlertMessage>{message}</AlertMessage>
      <RetryButton onClick={reload} />
    </AlertBody>
  </AlertLayout>

  // Over this
  <div role="alert" className="flex items-start gap-3 rounded border ...">
    <WarningIcon />
    <div className="flex min-w-0 flex-1 flex-col gap-3">
      <p className="font-medium text-bright">{message}</p>
      <button onClick={reload}>Try again</button>
    </div>
  </div>
  ```
- **Use the compound component pattern only for dynamic composition** — where the caller needs control over what is rendered and in what order. Do not use it for static layouts where the structure is always the same; named layout components are simpler and sufficient there. A compound component is appropriate when different call sites assemble genuinely different combinations of parts.
- Prefer **co-located UI** under `apps/client/src/features/<feature>/...` for feature-specific components.
- When a component has **child components**, use a folder structure:
  ```
  ComponentName/
  ├── index.tsx          # Main component
  └── components/        # Child components
      └── ChildName.tsx
  ```
- Keep **state co-located** — lift only when siblings need to coordinate; split large contexts into focused hooks.
- Keep changes **lint-clean**; prefer ESLint fixes on save (or run `pnpm turbo lint` after changes).
- TypeScript:
  - Prefer `type` for props.
  - When wrapping DOM elements, prefer `ComponentPropsWithoutRef<'...'>` and pass through props.
- React context values:
  - Never pass an inline object literal as a context value (e.g. `<Ctx value={{ a, b }}>`). A new object is created on every render, so every consumer re-renders even when `a` and `b` are unchanged — shallow comparison always fails on object identity.
  - Prefer **splitting into focused contexts**, one per logical concern, so a consumer only re-renders when its specific slice of state changes. This is always better than `useMemo` because it eliminates the re-render at the source rather than suppressing it downstream. See `useChatContext.tsx` for the established pattern (`ChatActionsContext`, `ChatStatusContext`, `ChatMessagesContext`).
  - Only fall back to `useMemo` for the context value when splitting contexts would require significant restructuring and the performance impact is low.
- `React.memo` and memoisation:
  - Before suggesting `React.memo`, verify that **all** props will be stable across renders via shallow comparison.
  - Object and array props (e.g. items from a state array, context values, derived objects) produce new references on every render and cause memo to fail unless the parent explicitly stabilises them with `useMemo`/`useCallback` or the library guarantees reference identity for unchanged entries.
  - Function props must be wrapped in `useCallback` with stable deps — or read via a ref — to be stable.
  - `React.memo` on a component whose parent re-renders with unstable prop references adds reconciliation overhead with no benefit; only suggest it when reference stability of every prop can be confirmed or is being fixed in the same change.
